When two or more classes inherit a single class, it is known as hierarchical inheritance.

            Class A  (Super Class)

          /    |    \  Inherits

   Class B  Class C  Class D  (Sub Classes)

Example:

class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("eating...");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("barking...");
    }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    void meow() {
        System.out.println("meow.. meow..");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        Cat c = new Cat();
        c.meow();
        c.eat();
        // c.bark(); // Compile Time Error

        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.bark();
        d.eat();
    }
}

Output:
meow.. meow..
eating...
barking...
eating...

In this example, both `Dog` and `Cat` classes inherit the `Animal` class — hierarchical inheritance.

