- `super` is used to refer to the immediate parent class instance variable.
- `super` is used to call a parent class method.
- Used when a subclass overrides a method and wants to access the parent class method.
- `super()` is used to call the parent class constructor, It must be the first statement inside the child constructor.
- Helps in initializing parent class properties.
- `super` cannot be used inside a static area.

Example:

class Animal {
    String color = "White";

    Animal() {
        System.out.println("Animal constructor");
    }

    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Animal is eating");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    String color = "Brown";

    Dog() {
        super();  // calling parent constructor — must be first statement
        System.out.println("Dog constructor");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Child color: " + color);          // Dog's color
        System.out.println("Parent color: " + super.color);   // Animal's color
        super.eat();                                           // calling parent method
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.display();
    }
}

Output:
Animal constructor
Dog constructor
Child color: Brown
Parent color: White
Animal is eating

This example demonstrates all three uses of `super` — accessing the parent instance variable (`super.color`), calling the parent method (`super.eat()`), and calling the parent constructor (`super()`).

